      <profileDesc>
         <abstract>
            <p>Dresselhaus<ref type="bibr" target="#b1"/> asked recently why scanning tunnelling microscopy
and spectroscopy experiments<ref type="bibr" target="#b2"/>,<ref type="bibr" target="#b3"/> find a similar
number of peaks, in the density of states near the Fermi level, for a range
of semiconducting single-wall carbon nanotubes with roughly the same diameters.
After all, semiconducting achiral zigzag single-wall nanotubes can have translational
unit cells more than an order of magnitude smaller than those of chiral semiconducting
single-wall nanotubes with a similar diameter, so they might be expected to
have fewer but sharper peaks in their density of states<ref type="bibr" target="#b1"/>. We
show that all semiconducting single-wall nanotubes with similar diameters
should have a similar density of states near the Fermi level, independent
of translational unit cell size or chiral angle.</p>
         </abstract>
