   <text>
      <body>
         <p>A single-wall nanotube (SWNT) can be constructed by rolling up a single
sheet of graphite (graphene) along one of its two-dimensional lattice vectors <hi rend="bold">
R</hi> = <hi rend="italic">n</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">1</hi>
            <hi rend="bold">R</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">1</hi>+<hi rend="italic">n</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">2</hi>
            <hi rend="bold">R
</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">2</hi> to form an (<hi rend="italic">n</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">1</hi>, <hi rend="italic">n</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">2</hi>) nanotube
with diameter <hi rend="italic">D</hi> = |<hi rend="bold">R</hi>|/π. To a first approximation, the allowed
electron states of the SWNT are the graphene bands satisfying the periodic
boundary conditions <hi rend="bold">k</hi>*<hi rend="bold">R</hi> = 2π<hi rend="italic">m</hi>, with <hi rend="italic">m</hi>
being an integer.</p>
         <p>Graphically, these allowed <hi rend="bold">k</hi>values lie along the parallel lines
in <ref type="figure" target="#f1">Fig. 1a</ref>, which are perpendicular to <hi rend="bold">R</hi> with
an interline spacing of 2/<hi rend="italic">D</hi>. The Fermi level, <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>,
is given by states at the corner points of the hexagonal Brillouin zone in <ref type="figure" target="#f1">Fig. 1a</ref>. So, neglecting the effects of curvature, nanotubes
are either metallic or semiconducting depending on whether or not
<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>*<hi rend="bold">R</hi> = 2π<hi rend="italic">m</hi>, where <hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> = 4π(<hi rend="bold">
R</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">1</hi>-<hi rend="bold">R</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">2</hi>)/9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>
            <hi rend="superscript">2</hi> and <hi rend="italic">
d</hi> is the carbon-carbon bond distance<ref type="bibr" target="#b4"/>.</p>
         <p>The two-dimensional dispersion relation of the occupied states of graphene
is given to lowest order in <hi rend="italic">d</hi>|<hi rend="bold">k</hi>-<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>|
by <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>_(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>) = -<formula/> |<hi rend="italic">V</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">ppπ</hi>|<hi rend="italic">d</hi>|<hi rend="bold">k</hi>-<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>|,
where <hi rend="italic">V</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">ppπ</hi>is the nearest-neighbour ppπ interaction<ref type="bibr" target="#b5"/>. Hence, near <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>, <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>_(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>)
is radially symmetric about the point <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> located by <hi rend="bold">k
</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> and decreases with increasing |<hi rend="bold">k</hi>-<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">
F</hi>|.</p>
         <p>For semiconducting SWNTs, the point of closest approach to <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">
F</hi>in any allowed line therefore yields to good approximation a local
maximum in the one-dimensional band structure as long as <hi rend="italic">d</hi>|<hi rend="bold">k</hi>-<hi rend="bold">
k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>| &lt; 1, leading to a van Hove singularity and a divergence
in the occupied density of states (DOS) near <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>. These
special points also yield peaks in the unoccupied DOS because the dispersion
relation for the unoccupied states is given by <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">+</hi>(<hi rend="bold">
k</hi>) = -<hi rend="italic">ε</hi>_(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>). The special point on the line closest
to <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> (labelled as <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">A</hi>in <ref type="figure" target="#f1">
Fig. 1b</ref>) also yields the SWNT band gap<ref type="bibr" target="#b5"/>,<ref type="bibr" target="#b6"/>.
This point is separated from <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> by a distance |<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">
A</hi>-<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>| = <formula/>, one-third the interline spacing - a result easily confirmed by
projecting <hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">A</hi>-<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> along <hi rend="bold">R</hi>.
So <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">A</hi>generates peaks in the DOS near <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">
±</hi>(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">A</hi>) = ±|<hi rend="italic">V</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">ppπ</hi>|<hi rend="italic">
d</hi>/<hi rend="italic">D</hi> and a band gap near 2|<hi rend="italic">V</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">ppπ</hi>|<hi rend="italic">d</hi>/<hi rend="italic">
D</hi> when <formula/>&lt;
1.</p>
         <p>Incrementing by the interline spacing, 2/<hi rend="italic">D</hi>, the next two special
points yield peaks in the DOS near <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">±</hi>(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">
B</hi>) = 2<hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">±</hi>(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">A</hi>) = ±2|<hi rend="italic">
V</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">ppπ</hi>|<hi rend="italic">d</hi>/<hi rend="italic">D</hi> when <formula/>&lt; 1, and peaks near <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">±</hi>(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">
C</hi>) = 4<hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">±</hi>(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">A</hi>) = ±4<hi rend="italic">
V</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">ppπ</hi>
            <hi rend="italic">d</hi>/<hi rend="italic">D</hi> when <formula/> &lt; 1. Changing chirality at a given SWNT diameter effectively rotates
the lines of allowed states around <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> without changing the
distances between the points along the lines and <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi>. Therefore
the DOS of two semiconducting SWNTs with differing chiral angles but similar
diameters are similar in the vicinity of <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> because <hi rend="italic">
ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">±</hi>(<hi rend="bold">k</hi>) is radially symmetric about <hi rend="italic">k</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">
F</hi>. A parallel analysis shows that all metallic SWNTs with similar diameters
have similar DOS near <hi rend="italic">ε</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">F</hi> within the graphene sheet model
but with peaks close to ±3|<hi rend="italic">V</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">ppπ</hi>|<hi rend="italic">d</hi>/<hi rend="italic">D
</hi> when <formula/> &lt;1.
</p>
         <p>All of these predictions are consistent with the numerical results shown
in <ref type="figure" target="#f1">Fig. 1c</ref>. Because the semiconducting and metallic
SWNTs studied experimentally all have <hi rend="italic">d</hi>/<hi rend="italic">D</hi>≈0.1 and <hi rend="italic">V</hi>
            <hi rend="subscript">
ppπ</hi>≈2.7 eV, these predictions explain the observed peak spacing
in the SWNT DOS<ref type="bibr" target="#b2"/>,<ref type="bibr" target="#b3"/>, further confirming the band
structure theory of these nanowires<ref type="bibr" target="#b4 b5 b6 b7 b8 b9"/>.</p>
